\i0  things like clean clothes, a new pair of boots, and even books.
\i \

\i0 \'93I can\'92t read,\'94 she told him.
\i \

\i0 \'93I could teach you,\'94 he answered.
\i \

\i0 \'93Why?\'94 she asked. It was a question she asked every time she met him, without fail. No one had been kind to her without reason.
\i \

\i0 One day, he finally answered honestly.
\i \

\i0 \'93You have a talent that I believe could be useful to me.\'94
\i \

\i0 She didn\'92t understand.
\i \

\i0 \'93I want to hire you,\'94 he said.
\i \

\i0 \'93I\'92m not for sale,\'94 she spat.
\i \

\i0 He smiled. \'93I mean to say that I wish to hire you as a thief,\'94 he explained.
\i \

\i0 \'93Oh,\'94 said Annabel, feeling silly. That wasn\'92t what she thought he\'92d meant. \'93What do you want me to steal?\'94
\i \

\i0 When he told her, Annabel nodded.
\i \

\i0 \'93I\'92ll do it,\'94 she said. \'93I\'92m Annabel, by the way.\'94
